":"1395","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","26 AUG 1371":"26. august 1371","1357":"1357","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","AFT 1395":"efter 1395","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Welles, Lincoln, England, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1357–1371":"1357–1371","1359–Female":"1359–Overleden","1415 AD":"1415","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","26 AUG 1371":"26 augustus 1371","1357":"1357","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","AFT 1395":"na 1395","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Welles, Lincoln, England, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1357–1371":"1357–1371","1359–Female":"1359–Deceased","1415 AD":"1415","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","26 AUG 1371":"26 August 1371","1357":"1357","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","AFT 1395":"after 1395","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Welles, Lincoln, England, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Willes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Wills  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wills","meanings":["English and German: variant of   Will   with genitival <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Richard Willes was born in 1370, in Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England, his father, Richard I Plantagenet York Fitz Wylls, was 13 and his mother, Marian Vycaryes, was 11. He married Mary Medows. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1453, in his hometown, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1357–1371":"1357–1371","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1415 AD":"1415","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","26 AUG 1371":"26. august 1371","1357":"1357","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","AFT 1395":"pärast 1395","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Welles, Lincoln, England, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1357–1371":"1357–1371","1359–Female":"1359–Kuollut","1415 AD":"1415","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","26 AUG 1371":"26. elokuuta 1371","1357":"1357","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","AFT 1395":"1395 jälkeen","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Welles, Lincoln, England, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1357–1371":"1357–1371","1359–Female":"1359–Décédée","1415 AD":"1415","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1359":"1359","26 AUG 1371":"26 août 1371","1357":"1357","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","AFT 1395":"après 1395","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, Angleterre","Welles, Lincoln, England, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , Engl